(just as an example) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#112512><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/unumenorean.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Numenorean</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_ball.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Druzzil Ro Member</span><br>  Posts: 140<br> <font color=#CCCCC8>(6/23/01 1:33:00 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://w3.one.net/~derek/201.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Inequity of Perception</span><hr size=1> LOL.<br>
<br>
Look this is a game. A silly game. Any positive relationship I strike up with someone by helping them in a difficult time is worth far more than any plat they would give. The best loot in this game is the friends you make a long the way. Not to mention it has a direct effect on your rep. Rep is invaluable.<br>
<br>
So I guess my question to all you people, regardless of class, haggling over whats a fair price to charge for your classes &quot;services&quot; is HOW much do you think your rep is worth? <br>
<br>
You might wanna start working on it from that perspective. <br>
<br>
I know if a rogue/monk dragged my corpse, wizard trans'd me, etc etc I would always be so kind as to &quot;tip&quot; them or pay them with some plat, minor item, etc for the help they gave me.....but when you start getting together to &quot;determine&quot; pricing, etc is when it begins to become uncool IMO.<br>
<br>
